51d05bd2-3fce-42c5-9427-d2b51e355b28.shortProfile: Today I watched a large spiny starfish moving in slow motion over a rock. Fleeing from its leading arm were 5 topshell molluscs. As they reached the edge of the rock instead of gliding over the edge they jumped into the abyss. They tumbled through the column of water landing safely on the sandy floor, now far in advance of the predatory starfish thanks to their clever leaping strategy. Because the starfish has sticky feet it can't release and do the same jump. But one topshell landed square on its back in the sand and no amount of "spinning" it's foot would get it upright. The huge starfish moved ominously down the rock heading for the trapped mollusk.  Then an amazing thing happened, another topshell changed direction and allowed the trapped animal to grab onto its shell and hitch a ride to safety. (I've seen this behaviour twice before and it's difficult to confirm if it happens by luck or if topshells are really saving their kin) .The starfish could not outrun the swifter topshells so it turned its attention to a nearby stationary urchin. The urchin had covered itself in two pieces of broken shell and one section of broken kelp. The starfish arm reared up and onto the urchins back clearly moving in for the kill. The sticky feet grabbed the protective covering of the kelp and shell, pulling them off the urchins back and giving the urchin vital seconds to escape. The adjacent urchin was not so lucky, having no protective covering. The starfish easily enveloped it, extruded its stomach and slowly began the process of digesting the urchin externally. This whole process from the start of the sea star chasing the topshells to its final kill took about 40 min.
51d05bd2-3fce-42c5-9427-d2b51e355b28.name: Marthasterias africana (Müller & Troschel, 1842)
